一、圖書作者與內容簡介：<BR>
High school student Clay Jenkins receives an anonymous package of tapes one day. When he listens to them, he discovers that they are from Hannah Baker, a girl he had a crush on prior to her suicide only days ago. At first, he’s skeptical, but then Hannah’s voice says that all thirteen people who received the tapes are a reason she died. And as Clay listens, he finds out life-changing things about his town and its people. <br />
<br />

<BR>
二、內容摘錄：<BR>
“The point is, when you hold people up for ridicule, you have to take responsibility when other people act on it.”-p.53<br />
<br />
“My world was collapsing. I needed those notes. I needed any hope those notes might have offered. And you? You took that hope away.”-p.165<br />
<br />
“If my love were an ocean, there would be no more land. If my love were a desert, you would see only sand. If my love were a star – late at night, only light. And if my love could grow wings, I’d be soaring in flight.”-p.177<br />
<br />
“When you mess with one part of a person’s life, you’re messing with their entire life. Everything . . . affects everything.”-p.201 <br />
<br />
“To miss her with a heart that feels so cold by itself, but warm when thoughts of her flow through me.”-p.219<br />
<br />

<BR>
三、我的觀點：<BR>
  Life is a fragile thing. One snip and all strings unravel.<br />
<br />
  How would you respond if you learned that you were in some way responsible for someone’s death?<br />
<br />
  In 13 Reasons Why, Clay Jensen got a box of tapes made by Hannah Baker, a girl he was very much in love with, until she ended her own life. She warned that there would be consequences should he ignore the tapes.<br />
<br />
  At first, the plot kind of scared me. I thought it was a ghost story, but when I made my way to the very end of the book, I realized that it was very, very human and that although I’ve never (and hope will never have to) experienced the kind of trauma Hannah went through that led up to her suicide, I can understand how it feels to just want to lock yourself up in your room and wonder why the world doesn’t end.<br />
<br />
  It’s not easy ending your own life. Really. Every time I see news about suicide, I wonder how they got up the courage to do so. Or, perhaps, calling it courage is wrong. The correct question should be: What on earth had happened to them that made their life so miserable that they felt they had no choice but to do so?<br />
<br />
  Hannah said in her recording that events others considered to be of little importance snowballed together until they rolled down the hill too fast to be stopped. Maybe what Jay Asher wants the reader to know is that every small thing matters. Every word, every action, and every thing that you didn’t think could possibly mean anything might be the straw that broke the camel’s back.<br />
<br />
  Personally, I still believe that, although whoever committed suicide is undeniably brave in some way, suicide is one of the ultimate cowardly acts. Once someone does something like that, they leave the people who do care about them with bleeding scars. There was a part when Hannah broke apart a moment with Clay abruptly because she was scared she’d have to go through the untrue rumors that surrounded her again. Clay asked her what was wrong. I think she should have told him. Since the book is written in alternative views, I could see that Clay would have listened. Yet Hannah had no way to see if he could really be trusted. She trusted others, including some of the other “reasons”, which only led to betrayal. I guess that when you have been betrayed to a certain number of times, you automatically shut people out.<br />
<br />
  One of the parts that made my heart ache the most was when Hannah was speaking through her tapes to a person who had stolen the notes of encouragement that other people had written to her, depriving her of any happiness people might have offered after reputation-crushing rumors and being harassed. I think that another thing Mr. Asher wanted to say is – just a few encouraging words, or anything that makes someone feel not so lonely on this vast planet, no matter how negligible, could literally save a life.<br />
<br />
  Everything affects everything, like Hannah said. Since no one can predict how their actions might affect another, you have to think about every move and every word before acting.  <br />
<br />
  What I learned from 13 Reasons Why can be summed up with this – Care about others. When you care about other people, you won’t do anything to harm them. You will want to protect them, and, most importantly, you will help them get through the low points of their lives.<br />
<br />
  The ending of the book gave me hope. When Clay watched another classmate who had, as he put it, “learned how to avoid people”, begin to disappear down the hall, maybe even towards the route Hannah ended up going down, he called her name. I thought, so things really can change. All you need is something that opens your eyes (or ears, in Clay’s case).<br />
<br />
  13 Reasons Why opened my eyes, and I hope that I can be a person who can help make the world a slightly better place.<br />
<br />

